ce:section.ce:para:
The capability of imaging-guided drug delivery of MFMSNs was revealed by confocal microscopy images of cellular uptake. MFMSNs could be taken up by U251 cells with incubation time, showing its imaging function via green fluorescence (Fig. 4
                     ). After loaded with DOX, both the green fluorescence of MFMSNs and red fluorescence of DOX could be both observed under a confocal microscope (Fig. 5
                     A–T and Fig. S14). The cellular uptake of the DOX-loaded MFMSNs (MFMSNDs) was both time-dependent (Fig. 5A–T) and concentration-dependent (Fig. S14). For 6-h incubation, MFMSNDs had reached nuclei and some of DOX separated from MFMSNs (Fig. 5A–E). When prolonging the incubation time, the uptake of MFMSNDs increased, and both the green and red fluorescence enhanced. For longer incubation times, for example, 18 and 24 h, the separation of MFMSNs and DOX was not so apparent because of both significantly enhanced fluorescence of MFMSNs and DOX within cells (Fig. 5K–T). From the results, the existence of MFMSNs within cells can be tracked using its fluorescence, which can be applied for imaging-guided drug delivery.
